<subSubSection pageId="115" pageNumber="116" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="115.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[707,889,150,177]" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">Atka Mackerel</emphasis>
or Northern Atka Mackerel. To at least 
<quantity box="[1363,1436,150,177]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" unit="cm" value="54.0">54 cm</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[206,288,187,214]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4102" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" unit="in" value="21.3">21.3 in</quantity>
) TL (Robert Lauth, pers. comm to M.L.). Sea of 
<collectingCountry box="[855,919,187,213]" name="Japan" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Antonenko, D. V. &amp; Kalchugin, P. V. &amp; Izmyatinskii, D. V. &amp; Kim, L. N." box="[935,1195,187,213]" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" pagination="54 - 57" refId="ref261490" refString="Antonenko, D. V., Kalchugin, P. V., Izmyatinskii, D. V. &amp; Kim, L. N. (2003) On the occurrence of cold-water species of fish, rare for Peter the Great Bay (the Sea of Japan). Journal of Ichthyology, 43, 54 - 57." type="journal article" year="2003">
Antonenko 
<emphasis box="[1070,1128,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">et al.</emphasis>
2003
</bibRefCitation>
) and Sea of Okhotsk (
<bibRefCitation author="Chereshnev and Nazarkin" box="[205,570,223,249]" firstAuthor="Chereshnev" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" pagination="307 - 311" refId="ref269576" refString="Chereshnev, I. A. &amp; Nazarkin, M. V. (2004) The first finding of the Atka mackerel Pleurogrammus monopterygius (Scorpaeniformes: Hexagrammidae) in the Tauiskaya Bay (northern part of the Sea of Okhotsk). Journal of Ichthyology, 44, 307 - 311." type="journal article" year="2004">Chereshnev and Nazarkin 2004</bibRefCitation>
) to Commanderâ€“Aleutian chain, and northern Bering Sea (Mecklenburg 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">et al.</emphasis>
2002) to Bering Strait (
<bibRefCitation author="Mecklenburg" box="[501,784,259,285]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Mecklenburg" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" pagination="109 - 140" refId="ref300975" refString="Mecklenburg, C. W., Moller, P. R. &amp; Steinke, D. (2011) Biodiversity of arctic marine fishes: taxonomy and zoogeography. Marine Biodiversity, 41, 109 - 140. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12526 - 010 - 0070 - z" type="journal article" year="2011">
Mecklenburg 
<emphasis box="[661,719,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
) to Redondo Beach, southern California (
<bibRefCitation author="Eschmeyer and Herald" firstAuthor="Eschmeyer" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" refId="ref277744" refString="Eschmeyer, W. N. &amp; Herald, E. S. (1983) A Field Guide to Pacific Coast Fishes of North America from the Gulf of Alaska to Baja California. Houghton Mifflin, Boston." type="book" year="1983">Eschmeyer and Herald 1983</bibRefCitation>
); rare in eastern North Pacific south of Alaska (Mecklenburg 
<emphasis box="[1036,1093,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">et al.</emphasis>
2002). Depth: lower intertidal to 
<quantity box="[228,300,331,357]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" unit="m" value="720.0">720 m</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[315,407,331,358]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.199375999999999" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" unit="ft" value="2362.0">2,362 ft</quantity>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Hoff and Britt" box="[430,661,331,357]" firstAuthor="Hoff" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" refId="ref285673" refString="Hoff, G. R. &amp; Britt, L. L. (2003) The 2002 Eastern Bering Sea upper continental slope survey of groundfish and invertebrate resources. National Marine Fisheries Service Technical Memorandum, NMFS-AFSC- 141." type="journal volume" year="2003">Hoff and Britt 2003</bibRefCitation>
). However, this latter is a record from a trawl-caught fish that might have been taken in midwater. Following 
<bibRefCitation author="Mecklenburg and Eschmeyer" box="[653,1065,367,393]" firstAuthor="Mecklenburg" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" refId="ref300717" refString="Mecklenburg, C. W. &amp; Eschmeyer, W. N. (2003) Family Hexagrammidae Gill 1889 - greenlings. California Academy of Sciences, Annotated Checklists of Fishes, No. 3." type="book" year="2003">Mecklenburg and Eschmeyer (2003)</bibRefCitation>
, we treat 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jordan &amp; Metz" authorityYear="1913" box="[1172,1436,367,393]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Hexagrammidae" genus="Pleurogrammus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="azonus">
<emphasis box="[1172,1436,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">Pleurogrammus azonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<collectingCountry box="[198,273,403,429]" name="Jordan" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">Jordan</collectingCountry>
&amp; Metz, 1913, a western Pacific form sometimes classified as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pallas" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[1240,1436,403,428]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Hexagrammidae" genus="Pleurogrammus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="monopterygius">
<emphasis box="[1240,1436,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">P. monopterygius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Nelson" box="[261,406,439,465]" firstAuthor="Nelson" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" refId="ref305011" refString="Nelson, J. S. (1994) Fishes of the World. John Wiley and Sons, New York." type="book" year="1994">Nelson 1994</bibRefCitation>
, Mecklenburg 
<emphasis box="[571,627,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">et al.</emphasis>
2002), as a distinct species with common name Southern Atka Mackerel or Arabesque Greenling. Molecular evidence recently presented by 
<bibRefCitation author="Crow" box="[966,1178,475,501]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Crow" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" pagination="986 - 997" refId="ref273186" refString="Crow, K. D., Kanamoto, Z. &amp; Bernardi, G. (2004) Molecular phylogeny of the hexagrammid fishes using a multi-locus approach. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 32, 986 - 997. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2004.03.012" type="journal article" year="2004">
Crow 
<emphasis box="[1037,1095,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="115" pageNumber="116">et al.</emphasis>
(2004)
</bibRefCitation>
supports the existence of two distinct species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
